  "why": "The CrossASR++ framework does not use iterative mutation of seed inputs, which circumvents the problem of cumulative distortion. Instead, it generates each test input (audio) from scratch using Text-to-Speech (TTS) systems based on text from a corpus. A TTS system is effectively a generative model trained to produce realistic and plausible human speech. This method directly aligns with the 'High' plausibility criteria of \"restricting search to a plausible input distribution (e.g., via a generative model trained to produce realistic inputs)\". The framework's design inherently assumes that the generated audio is plausible for its differential testing oracle to function correctly. This is further supported by how the framework handles implausible inputs: when an audio file cannot be recognized by any of the ASR systems, it is flagged as an \"indeterminable test case\" resulting from a potentially \"invalid audio\" generated by the TTS, rather than being treated as a valid failure.",
